<subSubSection pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="71.[151,1437,1160,1584]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1341,1367]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Remarks.</emphasis>
These hydroids resemble the trophosomes of several species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Oken, 1815" authorityName="Oken" authorityYear="1815" box="[1026,1270,1340,1367]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Halecium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1026,1135,1341,1367]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Halecium</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Oken, L." box="[1141,1270,1340,1367]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" refId="ref144798" refString="Oken, L. (1815) Okens Lehrbuch der Naturgeschichte. III. Theil. Zoologie. Vol. 1. Oken, Jena, 842 pp." type="book" year="1815">Oken, 1815</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
that have been reported from the Gulf of 
<collectingCountry box="[456,542,1377,1403]" name="Mexico" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Calder, D. R. &amp; Cairns, S. D." box="[558,819,1377,1403]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="381 - 394" refId="ref128090" refString="Calder, D. R. &amp; Cairns, S. D. (2009) Hydroids (Cnidaria: Hydrozoa) of the Gulf of Mexico. In: Felder, D. L. &amp; Camp, D. K. (Eds.), Gulf of Mexico. Origin, waters, and biota. Vol. 1. Biodiversity. Texas A &amp; M University Press, College Station, Texas, pp. 381 - 394." type="book chapter" year="2009">Calder &amp; Cairns 2009</bibRefCitation>
), including 
<taxonomicName authority="(Linnaeus, 1758)" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[956,1315,1376,1403]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Halecium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="halecinum">
<emphasis box="[956,1110,1377,1403]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">H. halecinum</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Linnaeus, C." box="[1127,1306,1376,1403]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" refId="ref139947" refString="Linnaeus, C. (1758) Systema naturae per regna tria naturae, secundum classes, ordines, genera, species cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis. Editio decima, reformata. Laurentii Salvii, Holmiae, 823 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 542" type="book" year="1758">Linnaeus, 1758</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Johnston, 1838)" authorityName="Johnston" authorityYear="1838" baseAuthorityName="Johnston" baseAuthorityYear="1838" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Halecium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="beanii">
<emphasis box="[1329,1436,1377,1403]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">H. beanii</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Johnston, G." box="[159,331,1413,1439]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" refId="ref136995" refString="Johnston, G. (1838) A history of the British zoophytes. W. H. Lizars, Edinburgh, 341 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 110844" type="book" year="1838">Johnston, 1838</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Norman, 1867" authorityName="Norman" authorityYear="1867" box="[353,633,1413,1439]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Halecium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="sessile">
<emphasis box="[353,461,1413,1439]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">H. sessile</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Norman, A. M." box="[468,633,1413,1439]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="193 - 206" refId="ref144348" refString="Norman, A. M. (1867) Report of the committee appointed for the purpose of exploring the coasts of the Hebrides by means of the dredge. - Part II. On the Crustacea, Echinodermata, Polyzoa, Actinozoa, and Hydrozoa. Report of the British Association for the Advancement of Science, Nottingham, 1866, 193 - 206." type="journal article" year="1867">Norman, 1867</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Allman, 1877" authorityName="Allman" authorityYear="1877" box="[644,1021,1413,1439]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Halecium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="macrocephalum">
<emphasis box="[644,857,1413,1439]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">H. macrocephalum</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Allman, G. J." box="[864,1021,1413,1439]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 66" refId="ref123138" refString="Allman, G. J. (1877) Report on the Hydroida collected during the exploration of the Gulf Stream by L. F. de Pourtales, assistant United States Coast Survey. Memoirs of the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard College, 5 (2), 1 - 66. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 15852" type="journal article" year="1877">Allman, 1877</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Congdon, 1907" authorityName="Congdon" authorityYear="1907" box="[1080,1432,1413,1439]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Haleciidae" genus="Halecium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="bermudense">
<emphasis box="[1080,1249,1413,1439]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">H. bermudense</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Congdon, E. D." box="[1256,1432,1413,1439]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="463 - 485" refId="ref129401" refString="Congdon, E. D. (1907) The hydroids of Bermuda. Proceedings of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, 42, 463 - 485. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 20022242" type="journal article" year="1907">Congdon, 1907</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. In lacking female gonophores, the specimens cannot be reliably identified to species. Colonies were strongly polysiphonic, with alternate and predominantly pinnate side branches; hydranths bore 20+ tentacles and the cnidome comprised both pseudostenoteles (10.2–12.0 long x 5.4 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[773,787,1521,1547]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">–</emphasis>
7.0 μm wide) and microbasic mastigophores (ca. 6.0 long x 1.8 μm wide).
</paragraph>
